  "text": "The LLVM IR type system to code generation chain flows through multiple layers of abstraction, starting from high-level Type classes and ending at machine-level type actions.\n\n## Type Creation and Management\n\nThe type hierarchy starts with the base `Type` class in `llvm/include/llvm/IR/Type.h` (line 45). This class uses an immutable singleton pattern where only one instance of each type exists in memory. Types are created via static factory methods and stored in an `LLVMContext`. The `Type` class contains a reference to its owning `LLVMContext` (line 83) and stores type metadata in the `ID` field and `SubclassData`.\n\nDerived types are defined in `llvm/include/llvm/IR/DerivedTypes.h`:\n- `IntegerType` (line 42): Represents arbitrary-width integer types with bitwidth stored in SubclassData\n- `FunctionType` (line 105): Represents function signatures with return type and parameters\n- `StructType` (line 218): Represents structured aggregate types\n\nImplementation details are in `llvm/lib/IR/Type.cpp`.\n\n## Context Ownership and Type Uniquing\n\nThe `LLVMContext` class in `llvm/include/llvm/IR/LLVMContext.h` (line 68) manages the ownership and uniquing of all types within a compilation unit. It holds a pointer to `LLVMContextImpl` (line 70), which is the opaque implementation.\n\nIn `llvm/lib/IR/LLVMContextImpl.h`, the `LLVMContextImpl` class (line 1620) maintains several type uniquing data structures:\n- `IntegerTypes` (line 1759): DenseMap storing IntegerType instances indexed by bit width\n- `FunctionTypeSet` (line 1761-1762): FoldingSet for unique FunctionType instances\n- `AnonStructTypes` and `NamedStructTypes` (lines 1764-1765): Sets for StructType uniquing\n- `ArrayTypes`, `VectorTypes`, `PointerTypes` (lines 1771-1774): Maps for other type instances\n\nThese structures use custom key info classes like `FunctionTypeKeyInfo` (line 140) and `AnonStructTypeKeyInfo` (line 93) for hashing and equality checking.\n\n## IR Type to EVT Conversion\n\nThe conversion from IR types to Extended Value Types (EVT) happens in the code generation phase. The `EVT` struct in `llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/ValueTypes.h` (lines 35-39) can represent both simple Machine Value Types (MVT) and extended types that aren't natively supported by any target.\n\nThe conversion functions are in `llvm/lib/CodeGen/ValueTypes.cpp`:\n- `EVT::getEVT()` (line 301): Converts an LLVM Type* to EVT, handling IntegerType, VectorType, and other types by dispatching to MVT::getVT() for standard types\n- `EVT::getTypeForEVT()` (line 218): Reverse conversion from EVT back to IR Type\n- `MVT::getVT()` (line 249): Converts Type* to MVT for simple types\n- `EVT::getIntegerVT()`, `EVT::getVectorVT()`: Factory methods for creating extended types\n\nFor extended types, the EVT stores a pointer to the original LLVM Type (line 38: `Type *LLVMTy`), maintaining the connection back to the IR representation.\n\n## SelectionDAG Type Legalization\n\nThe `SelectionDAGBuilder` in `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/SelectionDAGBuilder.cpp` converts IR instructions to SelectionDAG nodes, calling `visit()` methods (line 1371) that use EVT to represent value types.\n\nType legalization happens in the `DAGTypeLegalizer` class in `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeTypes.h` (line 31). This class:\n- Calls `getTypeAction()` (line 62) to determine how types should be legalized\n- Maintains transformation maps for different legalization strategies:\n  - `PromotedIntegers` (line 98): For promoting small integers to legal widths\n  - `ExpandedIntegers` (line 102): For expanding integers into multiple values\n  - `SoftenedFloats` (line 106): For converting floats to integers\n  - `PromotedFloats` (line 110): For promoting float precision\n  - `ScalarizedVectors` (line 122): For converting vectors to scalars\n  - `SplitVectors`, `WidenedVectors` (lines 126, 130): For vector transformations\n\nThe legalization process is implemented in `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeTypes.cpp` and companion files:\n- `LegalizeIntegerTypes.cpp`: Integer legalization strategies\n- `LegalizeFloatTypes.cpp`: Floating-point legalization\n- `LegalizeVectorTypes.cpp`: Vector type legalization\n- `LegalizeVectorOps.cpp`: Vector operation legalization\n\n## Type Action Configuration\n\nThe target-specific type legalization actions are configured in `TargetLowering` class in `llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/TargetLowering.h`. The `ValueTypeActionImpl` (line 1112) stores a bitvector of type actions for each simple value type:\n- `TypeLegal`: Type is supported natively\n- `TypePromoteInteger`: Promote to larger integer\n- `TypeSoftenFloat`: Convert float to integer\n- `TypeExpandInteger`: Expand into multiple values\n- `TypeExpandFloat`: Expand float into multiple values\n- `TypeScalarizeVector`: Convert vector to scalar\n- `TypeSplitVector`: Split vector into parts\n- `TypeWidenVector`: Widen vector to legal width\n\nThe `TargetLoweringBase::computeRegisterProperties()` function in `llvm/lib/CodeGen/TargetLoweringBase.cpp` (line 1656) initializes these actions based on the target's register and instruction set capabilities.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe type system flow is: `Type` → `LLVMContext` (manages uniquing) → `EVT` (extends to non-native types) → `DAGTypeLegalizer` (applies target-specific legalization) → `TargetLowering::getTypeAction()` (determines transformation strategy) → Machine types."
